data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## The Problem: C# 14 Span Overload Resolution

In C# 14 / .NET 10, new built-in span conversions change overload resolution. When you call `.Contains()` on an `int[]`, the compiler now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)`** instead of **`Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`**.

`MemoryExtensions.Contains` is **not representable in expression trees** (expression trees don't support `Span<T>`), so it throws at runtime — typically an `InvalidOperationException` or `NotSupportedException`.

## The Fix

Cast or convert the array to `IEnumerable<T>` so the compiler selects `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 3: call Enumerable.Contains directly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is expression-tree-compatible. `.AsEnumerable()` is the most idiomatic.
